[2] Mexico (Tamaulipas), suspected
Date: Thu 15 Jan 2009
Source: Milenio.com [Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.milenio.com/node/148675>


Health authorities called a meeting to deal with fear that a dengue
outbreak was occurring. Just 2 weeks into the new year [2009], the
health sector has detected 35 suspected [dengue] cases. There are 19
neighborhoods in the southern zone at high risk [of dengue].

Thursday morning [15 Jan 2009], the Health authorities held a meeting
with personnel from the southern zone to reinforce actions to combat
dengue in 8 neighborhoods in Tampico, 8 in Madero and 2 in Altamira,
where the suspected dengue cases have occurred. According to Ernesto
Lavin, in charge of the unit, the presence of the [dengue virus]
mosquito vector has increased in the 1st months [weeks?] of January
2009, due to prevalence of hot weather, which favors its reproduction.

He said that tests on the 35 people who had symptoms of the disease
are being done, and the results are awaited.

The southern zone of Tamaulipas is the main [focus] with the greatest
incidence of officially recognized dengue cases. Again, as in 2007,
the municipalities of Tampico, Madero and Altamira had 50 percent of
the ill individuals. That situation is attributed to migratory
movement, high humidity, which has occurred this year [2009], and
natural wetlands in which there are places bordering lake systems,
where there is risk and conditions appropriate for [dengue vector
mosquito] proliferation. [This last statement is not correct. _Aedes_
mosquitoes that transmit dengue virus do not breed in natural
wetlands, rather in water catchments in and immediately around
buildings, as indicated below. - Mod.TY]

Alfredo Rodriguez Trujillo, epidemiologist with the state Secretariat
of Health, said that they have been working closely in the 43
Tamaulipas municipalities, where they have exhorted the populace to
undertake action to combat dengue by means of cleaning up homes,
avoiding accumulation of rain water in containers, which is where the
dengue mosquito vector reproduces.

He explained that during 2008, Tamaulipas recorded a reduction in the
numbers of dengue cases of almost 50 percent, having detected just
1100 who suffered [dengue], in comparison with the previous year
[2007], when more than 2000 cases of this [potentially] fatal disease occurred.

[Byline: Anahy Meza]

