[4] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Fri 16 Jan 2009
Source: Correio [Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://correio24horas.globo.com/noticias/noticia.asp?codigo=15749&mdl=50>


An outbreak of dengue fever reached the city of Jequie, located in
the south of Bahia state, 365 km [226 mi] from Salvador. According
Stela Santos Souza, Secretary of Health of the city, just in the 1st
16 days of 2009, there were 787 reported cases of the disease. Of
these, 266 have been [laboratory] confirmed. The cases that have not
yet been confirmed are being analyzed by the municipal Secretariat of
Health and depend on results of serological tests.

This [current number of dengue cases] is 18 percent more cases
compared with 2007.

"The figures are alarming, especially because the vast majority of
the cases have reached the vicinity of the Juaquirumao neighborhood
in the periphery of the city. It is curious that last year [2008],
there were scarcely any cases in this neighborhood," underscored the Secretary.

A medical team from the Ministry of Health coordinated by Dr. Agnaldo
Rico indicated that a boy of 7 years is a suspected dengue victim who
died of DHF. Another 2 cases that were being investigated were
negative by serological tests.

According to the Ministry of Health, the outbreak of dengue in Jequie
has 2 sources: the heavy rains that hit the city in November [2008]
after a period of drought (which increased the rate of illegal
storage of water) combined with the neglect of the population in
preventing it [creation of _Aedes_ breeding sites].

"The secretary of health carried out educational actions in
districts, but the population needs to collaborate [more]," the
secretary stressed.

Besides Jequie, other municipalities of the south center are affected
by dengue (Jaguaquara, Mucuge, Manoel Vitorino and Ipiau). However,
there is still no confirmation that they are having an outbreak of the disease.

Salvador has a high risk of dengue. Around 3600 cases were registered
in the capital in 2008, an increase of 65 percent in relation to
2007. The places most affected were the districts of the Peninsula de
Itapagipe and Suburbio Ferroviario.

In 2008, the household index of [_Aedes_] infestation (IIP) was 3.4
in the city, with the Uruguay neighborhood reaching the alarming
number of 7.0, which means that for each 100 properties visited, 7
had [_Aedes_] mosquito larvae. The situation is considered high risk
[for dengue virus transmission], with an IIP of 3.9 [or above]. In
2007, the index in the whole city was 4.6.

The city of Salvador announced this Tuesday [13 Jan 2009] the
creation of a contingency plan to prevent a dengue epidemic of the
disease during the summer.

In 2008, according to the State Secretariat of Health of Bahia, 35
972 cases of dengue were registered in the Bahia municipalities. Of
these, 14 people died.

--
