[5] Bolivia (tropical lowlands)
Date: Wed 14 Jan 2009
Source: La Prensa, Bolivia [edited]
<http://www.laprensa.com.bo/noticias/14-01-09/14_01_09_socd5.php>,


The government has declared a dengue health emergency in the
departments [state or province equivalent - Mod.TY] of Santa Cruz,
Beni, Pando and Cochabamba due to the appearance of at least 250
dengue cases so far this year [2009].

The Director of Epidemiology, Juan Carlos Arraya, said that the
regions affected by the disease [virus], transmitted by a mosquito,
are Villa Tunari in Cochabamba; Riberalta in Beni; Cobija in Pando
and the city of Santa Cruz. He pointed out that 80 percent of the
cases, which are not necessarily all of them because people who have
symptoms do not go to health centers, are found in Santa Cruz.

The official indicated that during the past season [2008], 2000
laboratory confirmed dengue cases were attended to, with 11 of DHF, 9
of which were detected in Santa Cruz and 2 in Pando.

The [health] authority explained that the declaration of a health
emergency assumes a coordinated effort everywhere in order to avoid
this disease, which can cause deaths.

Among the expected activities are fumigation of [mosquito] infested
places, elimination of [_Aedes_ mosquito] breeding sites, and
provision of clean water to families that live in these areas, among others.

A fundamental part of this effort will be the armed forces, 14 800 of
whom will be working during this emergency and will provide vehicles,
and, in some cases, their own fumigation and dengue control equipment.

The emergency will last for 3 months, the time that corresponds to
the rainy season in the country, which is exactly the time of
increase of the disease.

Among the other designated measures to stop this disease, which
particularly attacks the poorest regions because they lack basic
services and hygiene, is a long-term strategy (2008-2013) the object
of which is to maintain the DHF mortality level at 0 and the levels
of household infestation at less than 5 percent. [Note: this may not
be adequate to prevent dengue virus transmission. See the Brazil
item, above. - Mod.TY]

The Minister of Health, Ramiro Tapia, pointed out the declaration of
emergency requires that all the hospitals and medical and health
centers attend [to patients] to the maximum of their capability.

--
