[9] New Caledonia
Date: Tue 13 Jan 2009
Source: Romandie News [French, machine trans., edited]
<http://www.romandie.com/infos/news2/090112235549.2qfkr644.asp>


Health authorities in New Caledonia are concerned about the
development of the dengue epidemic, with nearly 100 new patients
since the beginning of January [2009], as reported Tuesday [13 Jan 2009].

"We have 91 cases since the beginning of the year [2009]. The
situation is worrying, and we think it will get worse given the
weather," said AFP Aurelie Guigon, head of virology at the Institut Pasteur.

The weather has been warm and very wet currently in New Caledonia,
promoting the development of the mosquitoes that are the main vehicle
of transmission of the disease [virus].

In addition to the weather, the recent appearance in the archipelago
of dengue type 4 [virus] is another cause for concern.

"There are now 2 dengue virus serotypes: Type 1, which is usual here,
and type 4 against which the Caledonians are not immune. There is no
cross-immunity with dengue; the risk is doubled," Guigon also indicated.

In 2008, 1135 cases of dengue were reported, with a surge in the
epidemic around February-March 2008 and a fatal case in October 2008.
Last year [2008], over the 1st 15 days of January, there were only 5 cases.

"We need a little more background, but the issue of endemism
[endemnicity?] of dengue in New Caledonia arises," said Aureie Guigon.

The authorities have recommended that the population destroy all
mosquito breeding places, such as under plant pots or in children's
toys in the garden, and to use regular insect repellant lotions.

With each report of a case, the area surrounding the houses of the
sick are sprayed with insecticides, but spraying massively and
constantly has led to resistance of mosquitoes beginning in 2003.

Poorly equipped, small inland municipalities do not always follow
this procedure.

